So, this question mainly arised thanks to posts like these:&lt;br&gt;
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2570552/why-are-new-delete-slower-than-malloc-free
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Consider yourself in a situation where:&lt;br&gt;

 - you mainly work with plain old data types, and you have to do a lot
   of allocations/deallocations
 - you work with contiguous memory blocks
 - for some reason, performance really, really matters...

&lt;br&gt;
The idea is, to come up with a new allocator class, which can &quot;choose&quot; between the two methods, namely `new` and `malloc()`. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Let&#39;s say you will use `std::allocator` if your type &lt;b&gt;is not&lt;/b&gt; a POD type,&lt;br&gt; and use an allocator like this one, described here: https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/named_req/Allocator (Mallocator) &lt;br&gt; if your type &lt;b&gt;is&lt;/b&gt; a POD type
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
And now, to select your allocator class, you will use something like this:&lt;br&gt;
```C++
namespace meta
{

    template&lt;bool, typename T&gt;
    struct Allocator_Impl;

    template&lt;typename T&gt;
    struct Allocator_Impl&lt;true, T&gt;
    {
        using type = Mallocator&lt;T&gt;;
    };

    template&lt;typename T&gt;
    struct Allocator_Impl&lt;false, T&gt;
    {
        using type = std::allocator&lt;T&gt;;
    };

    template&lt;typename T&gt;
    struct is_trivially_allocateable
    {
        using type = typename
        std::conjunction&lt;std::is_trivial&lt;T&gt;,
                         std::is_standard_layout&lt;T&gt;&gt;::type;

        constexpr static inline bool value = type::value;
    };
}

template&lt;typename T&gt;
struct Allocator : public meta::Allocator_Impl&lt;meta::is_trivially_allocateable&lt;T&gt;::value, T&gt;
{};
```
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
After this, to implement our &quot;smart?&quot; container we can simply inherit from the good old `vector` class, for example. Let&#39;s say this vector here is somewhere in another namespace, for example `sna`:&lt;br&gt;
```C++
namespace sna
{
    template&lt;typename T&gt; using allocTy = typename Allocator&lt;T&gt;::type;


    template&lt;typename T, class Alloc = allocTy&lt;T&gt;&gt;
    class vector : public std::vector&lt;T, Alloc&gt;
    {
    public:
        typedef typename std::vector&lt;T, Alloc&gt;::size_type size_type;
        typedef T value_type;
        typedef Alloc allocator;
        typedef std::vector&lt;value_type, allocator&gt; parent;

        vector() : parent() {}
        vector(const size_type n) :
            parent(n)
    
        ... implement other constructors if needed ...
    };
}
```
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
After this - just to make sure - I, too, benchmarked the allocation times and came up with:
&lt;br&gt;

&gt;Allocating 100000000 double:&lt;br&gt; 
&gt;Duration with normal vector:    281528400 ns.&lt;br&gt;
&gt;Duration with custom vector:    1990600 ns.

&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
For the benchmark I used this piece of code:
```C++
std::chrono::system_clock::time_point start, stop;

const size_t size = 100000000;
std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Allocating &quot; &lt;&lt; size &lt;&lt; &quot; doubles:&quot; &lt;&lt; std::endl;

start = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
std::vector&lt;double&gt; new_data(size);
stop = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Duration with normal vector: &quot;;
std::cout &lt;&lt; std::chrono::duration_cast&lt;std::chrono::nanoseconds&gt;(stop - start).count() &lt;&lt; &quot; ns.&quot; &lt;&lt; std::endl;

start = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
sna::vector&lt;double&gt; malloc_data(size);
stop = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Duration with custom vector: &quot;;
std::cout &lt;&lt; std::chrono::duration_cast&lt;std::chrono::nanoseconds&gt;(stop - start).count() &lt;&lt; &quot; ns.&quot; &lt;&lt; std::endl;
```

